                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100104">Germany</placeName>
                                </origPlace>, <origDate notAfter="1450" notBefore="1401">15th century, first half</origDate>. The listing in the calendar of <quote>dedicatio ecclesie pataviensis</quote> on August 5, as well as the celebration as festa fori of St Valentine (Jan. 7), his translation (Aug. 6), and of St Maximilian (Oct. 12), places the manuscript in the diocese of <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100280">Passau</placeName>
                                </origPlace>. The feast of the Visitation, instituted <date when="1389"/>, is present in the calendar, but the feast of the Transfiguration, instituted in <date when="1457"/> (and celebrated in Passau on August 26), is not, which indicates a production date within this period.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>On <locus from="1v" to="1v" scheme="folios"/>, a former owner identifies himself as Symon Poth, stating that the manuscript was sold to him by Walthisar Honsperger, chaplain of the Altar of the Holy Cross, on February 24, <date when="1480"/>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>The manuscript came to the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">Royal Library</orgName> before the fire of <date when="1697"/>; it was most likely brought to Sweden in the 17th century as spoils of war from the Thirty Years' War. It is listed as <quote>233 </quote> in Jaches's catalogue of 1698 (U 122; former signum <quote>238</quote>), as <quote>17</quote> in the catalogue of 1734 (U 125e), and as <quote>e.30.6.10</quote> in Hammarsköld's catalogue from the 19th century. The signum <quote>18 </quote> found on the spine has not been identified.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
